 tA Subject of Interest -- tThe Lure of the London Stage -- tHumouring the Jewish Agency -- tThe Fateful Sukkah Meeting -- tMy Brother - Yusuf -- tIn the Aftermath of the Six-Day War -- tA Critic at Large -- tKosher Style -- tBlack Cats versus White Cats -- tAn Immodest Proposal -- tHosanna -- tChomsky and I -- tFrom Providence to the Holy Land -- tThe Yom Kippur War -- tTouching the Past with Dieter -- tPfefferkorn versus the State of Israel -- tThe Latter-Day Hellenists -- tImitatio Dei -- tThe Bitburg Offence to Memory -- tThe Water Cooler Metaphor -- tIn Image and Word -- tThe Life of Pi -- tMy Secret Garden -- tSpeak No Evil of Man: He, Himself, is Testimony to It -- tThe Lost Generation -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWinner of the 2012 Helen and Stan Vine Canadian Jewish Book Award in Holocaust Literature. A survivor of concentration camps and the Death March, Eli Pfefferkorn looks back on his Holocaust and post-Holocaust experiences to compare patterns of human behavior in extremis with those of ordinary life. What he finds is that the concentration camp Muselmann, who has lost his hunger for life and is thus shunned by his fellow inmates on the soup line, bears an eerie resemblance to an office employee who has fallen from grace and whose coworkers avoid spending time with him at the water cooler. Though the circumstances are unfathomably far apart, the human response to their situations is triggered by self-preservation rather than by calculated evil. By juxtaposing these two separate worlds, Pfefferkorn demonstrates that ultimately the human condition has not changed significantly since Cain slew Abel and the Athenians sentenced Socrates.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Program  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC